 	<p n="1-10">Gho <gap reason="lost"/> Vraḥ, Gho <gap reason="lost"/>, Gho <gap reason="lost"/>, Gho <gap reason="lost"/>, Gvāl Candrabhāva, Gvāl <gap reason="lost"/>, Gvāl Kaṁpit, Gvāl <gap reason="lost"/>, Tai Pindu, Tai <gap reason="lost"/>, Tai <gap reason="lost"/>, Tai Gandha, Tai Kaṁpit, Tai Kanteṅ, Tai <gap reason="lost"/>, Tai <gap reason="lost"/>, Tai Kañjrai, Tai <gap reason="lost"/>, Tai Gandha, Tai Saṁ-ap, Tai <gap reason="lost"/>. Tatal: 8 male slaves <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>gho</foreign></supplied>, 6 animal keepers <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>gvāl</foreign></supplied>, <gap reason="lost"/>, 5 <gap reason="lost"/>, <gap reason="lost"/> girl <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tai rat</foreign></supplied>, a baby girl <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tai pau</foreign></supplied>; grand total <gap reason="lost"/>.</p>
              <p n="10-23">Village af Caṅciṅ: Si Kan, Gha <gap reason="lost"/>, <supplied reason="subaudible"></supplied> Sadāśiva <gap reason="lost"/>, Gha Kan-as, <gap reason="lost"/>, Gha Kansoy, Gho <gap reason="lost"/>, Gho Kaṁpur, Gho <gap reason="lost"/>, Gho Kan-in <gap reason="lost"/>, Gho Kaṁpit, Gha Śrī, Gvāl <gap reason="lost"/>, <supplied reason="subaudible">Gvāl</supplied> Thleṁ, Gvāl Gati with many bays called Thleṁ, <gap reason="lost"/>, Panlās, Pansa <gap reason="lost"/>, Tai Paras, Tai Kaṁpañ, Tai Pan-u, Tai Kaṁvrau, Tai Khnap, Tai Kañcyas, Tai Chpoṅ, Tai Thkyāp, Tai Krau, Tai Thleṁ, Tai Phtal, Tai Kañjaṅ, Tai Pandan, Tai Khmau, Tai Dharmma, Lap Kaṁpas, Lap Khnap, Lap Kan-in with a daughter <gap reason="lost"/>, Tai <!-- kuch: The inscription is incomplete. It may be continued to K. 183-30. --></p>
